<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DCLG Select Committee inquiry into whether and how fiscal and financial powers could be devolved to London and English cities</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission from Birmingham City Council (FDC30)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he leadership of Birmingham City Council strongly welcomes this inquiry as an opportunity to put over the case for fiscal and financial devolution.  The inquiry is timely in view of the joint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Centred Cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> campaign on these issues by the Core Cities, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">GLA, the Mayor of London and London Councils. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> That campaign is in turn based on the work of the London Finance Commission, which included our Chief Executive Stephen Hughes amongst the commission members.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Attached to this submission is Stephen’s most rec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent article for the Local Government Chronicle which gives further thoughts on these issues.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a member of the Core Cities group we fully support the group submission and this short document is intended simply to add further detail and examples from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">perspective of Birmingham and Greater Birmingham.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The specific policy options being considered in this inquiry need to be seen in the context of the wider need for radical reform in how we fund and organise our local public services and as part of a wider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consideration of the future role of local government and its contribution to economic policy.  In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we are developing a new model for “city government” involving a “triple devolution” to city regions, cities and neighbourhoods.  The full realisat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion of this model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will require devolution of funding, new freedoms and flexibilities and integration of public services.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The financial crisis facing many urban authorities in the next few years has been brought about because government has tried to force </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant cuts in funding through an essentially unreformed system.  As a result those areas which are most reliant on government grants have seen the largest cuts, to an extent that now threatens the provision of even statutory services, whilst others a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maintain services through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> council tax and retained business rates.  This situation means that reforms of the sort being considered by the committee are now not only desirable but essential as part of a wider reform to secure the future sustainab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ility of local government.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Put simply, if government wishes to run local public services at a significantly lower cost then it must implement the radical reforms necessary to make that achievable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (or face the consequence of ending many statutory service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> If the aim is to move towards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more autonomous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, less dependent on government grants, then government has to legislate to provide sufficient freedoms to generate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local income needed to finance an acceptable level of services.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> If we want t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o rebalance our economy and ensure that our great cities perform to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heir potential then we must enab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le the enterprising local leadership this will require.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The inquiry is an opportunity to make th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> point</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to all the political parties and to begin an honest debate about the way forward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the run up to the 2015 election</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Answers to specific questions in the call for evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How devolved areas would be defined geographically and set up</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our new model o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f city government we recognise that cities must be governed at three different levels and the role of leadership is very much about linking these together effectively.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The appropriate geography will depend on the funding being devolved or the freedoms bei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng granted.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Governance and accountability needs to be considered alongside the question of geography – some funding and powers may be appropriately given to fairly informal partnerships, but usually a formal level of government will be required.  There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is scope for debate about where policy should sit on the spectrum from optional “deals” agreed with each city to the creation of new governance structures, as was the case with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reforms of 2000.  Realistically any radical devolution will probably</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> require strong accountability and governance structures, rather than temporary or specific agreements between cities and government.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of investing in infrastructure, supporting the local labour market and planning strategically for housing and la</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd use will primarily be carried out at a metropolitan or city region level.  In the case of the cities this will commonly be the conurbations or city regions previously covered by metropolitan counties </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(as with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> case) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or the combined authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> now being developed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> most of the cities.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However if this level of governance is less formal then accountability will have to rest with primary local authorities – in this case the individual districts within the metropolitan area.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:20.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Financial reforms de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signed to support more integrated public services will be focused </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">initially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at the district level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, though there is scope to rethink these on a city regional basis, for example health and social care or community safety work with police services already ope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rating on a larger scale.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How public services, including employment, skills and welfare should be organised to complement devolution</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our new model of city government echoes the Core Cities call for more integrated public services at both city regional an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d city levels, with Place Based settlements for each area allowing us to plan the provision of all public services in a joined up way.  This is not just a question of creating nominal budgets and partnerships at the local level.  It will require </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whitehall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to operate in a new way, with budgets allocated by the Treasury to places as well as functional departments.  Departments would not be able to access funding unless they are signed up to this locally integrated approach.  This will be essential to the succ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ess of these reforms, as separate departmental budgets would mean that they continue to determine how money is spent in a silo based approach.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How devolved areas should be governed, including the role of business in decision making; how devolved areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">would be held to account</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have partly covered this question </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n paragraphs 6 to 9 above.  We believe it is important for the business community to be closely engaged in decision making related to how we support economic growth, the labour market and skil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ls.  The LEPs have been very variable in their effectiveness and in the strength of their partnership with councils.  We have had excellent business leadership in the Greater</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Birmingham and Solihull LEP, b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ut even the best business leaders cannot replace th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e democratically accountable role of the local authority and do not have the resources to support the range of services required, so the larger city councils have tended to take on most of the support to these partnerships, including the accountable body s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tatus for holding large amounts of public money.  Therefore we need to maintain the benefits of close partnership working with business but place LEPs in a consultative role, as is already the case in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Combined authorities seem to be the best avail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able model for governance and accountability at the city region level.  But we believe there is a good case for exploring the development of stronger government structures around this model, including the possibility of replicating the GLA and elected mayo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r model in the other cities.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Genuine local accountability must be based on freedom of local choice about the level of taxation and how funds are spent.  This means that the effective cap on council tax increases should be removed and further steps should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be taken to remove ring fences around specific budgets.  Central government must stop trying to “have it both ways” by using the language of localism and freedom whilst imposing formal and less formal restraints on local choice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The strength of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evidence that devolution would lead to economic growth, local improvement and better governance, including examples of what areas could do with their new powers such as use them to invest in infrastructure and local services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Core Cities submission pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ovides a good summary of the compelling evidence that greater freedom and devolution for cities leads to greater economic growth.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The future economy will be based on a global network of cities competing and collaborating with each other and the success of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> any nation will depend even more on the performance of its major cities.  Nations that give more freedom to their cities tend to have cities performing economically at above the national average, to the benefit of the national economy as a whole.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As we m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entioned in the introduction above, the case for reforming the funding of our local public services is even more critical.  The current system provides no freedom of movement for councils to raise the resources necessary to provide adequate services.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">council tax does not provide buoyancy and the banding system and valuations are decades out of date.  The tax is effectively capped and has been frozen for years and it provides only about a tenth of the spending of cities such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  Despite rece</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt reforms, business rates are still basically a national system of taxation.  Innovations to provide for incentives for local growth (such as the New Homes Bonus) are in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fact redistributing money from more deprived areas to those already experiencing grow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th.  The current system leaves too many councils dependent on government grants, whilst a lucky few are able to fund services from local resources.  The radical reform of this system is now long overdue and without reform it will be impossible to maintain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">adequate provision across the range of statutory services.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Through our work with Lord Heseltine on the Greater Birmingham Project (following his report No Stone Unturned) we also made the case for a significant single funding pot for infrastructure, skill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s and economic development.  The report makes the case by reference to a) the increased speed of decision making and implementation that can be achieved at a local level, b) the benefits of joining up funding to create an integrated, flexible and place foc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">used approach, c) improved accountability for local delivery and d) the potential for additional leverage of private sector funds through local partnerships and flexibility.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Specific local projects and programmes which the Greater Birmingham Project ide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntified included:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Improved business support through a proposal developed by the Birmingham Chambers of Commerce</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The M42 Gateway</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Birmingham Airport</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sector “acceleration zones” such as an advanced manufacturing hub and Life Sciences centre</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An integrated app</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roach to skills based on local priorities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Collaborative procurement across local authorities</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Whether reform of the existing system (e.g. re-banding council tax, revaluing business rates, community budgets, government grants, formulas and taxes such as sta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">mp duty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">) would be a precursor to, or run along with, large-scale institutional change</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We support the approach suggested by the Core Cities group submission – it is unrealistic to expect an entirely neat and orderly transition to a more devolved approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and we should not delay actions that can be taken immediately by waiting for structural changes or legislation that may take some years to arrive.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What changes should be made to devolved authorities borrowing powers?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As pointed out in the Core Cities gro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">up submission, the Prudential Borrowing legislation means that there is no need for additional regulation of borrowing, such as a cap.  The slight relaxation of the cap on HRA borrowing announced in Autumn Statement 2013 should be seen as a very small firs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t step towards a freer and more locally accountable borrowing regime.  The argument for this is particularly strong in the area of infrastructure investment, where a future asset is being created through borrowing.  In this area government should also take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the initial provisions for Tax Increment Financing to the next stage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quickly, by allowing more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> radical investment schemes, along the lines of those available to cities in the US.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The scope for areas to introduce new taxes and funding methods such as bond</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s and crowd sourcing, fees and charges.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The basic principle should be to create a significantly greater level of fiscal autonomy and accountability to the local electorate.  Some reforms will be designed to underpin the delivery of basic local services, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hile others may be tailored to specific economic development purposes and (as with Business Improvement Districts) developed in partnership with the local business community.  One example is the work we are doing in Birmingham to develop a Tourist BID mode</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l.  This would fund investment in local environment and facilities and a city’s cultural and entertainment offer through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contributions from hotels – possibly then leading to the development of a local bed tax, subject to legislation.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A more sustainable fi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nance system will also need to allocate resources much more efficiently to prevention and investment and away from funding the “costs of failure”.  Much more work should be done in partnership across government to establish the potential for innovative way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s of shifting funds from future savings to the current investments that can generate them.  There may be considerable scope for innovations such as social investment, crowd funding and payment by results.  There should be much wider adoption of the “earn b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ack” or “gain share” model that has now been agreed for the Greater Manchester City Deal, whereby economic growth provides returns for the local area and not just savings for the Treasury.  In Birmingham we have put forward a more specific earn back propos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al related to the jobs to be created through our Birmingham Energy Savers programme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What taxes might be devolved – for example council tax, stamp duty and business rates?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:14.32pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The aim of the reform of local funding and taxation should be to create more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">buoyancy in a system that currently has very little.  That is the only way in which areas currently struggling economically and with a high level of service needs will be able to sustainably become more independent.  So, in addition to the proposals put fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rward in the London Finance Commission report and the Centred Cities campaign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (and echoed in the Core Cities submission)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we also suggest that it is worth exploring the case for and practicalities of a local apportionment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of VAT going to local authorities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  VAT is much more responsive to local economic activity than property taxes such as business rates.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>